    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="598"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d598">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">815.0145/1</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Erwin</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 17</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-19">October 19,
                            1937</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatch no. 32
                    of October 1, 1937 referring to previous correspondence concerning the reported
                    search of the British motor vessel <hi rend="italic">Caoba</hi> by a Honduran
                    gunboat. You invite attention to the following provision of Article 153 of the
                    Honduran Constitution of 1936: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“To the State appertains the full dominion, inalienable and
                            inprescriptible, over the waters of the territorial seas to a distance
                            of twelve kilometers from the lowest tide mark …”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>It is desired that you advise the Honduran Foreign Office in writing that your
                    Government reserves all rights of whatever nature with regard to any effects
                    upon American interests from an enforcement of this Constitutional provision so
                    far as it asserts that the territorial waters of Honduras extend beyond the
                    three-mile limit.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sumner Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
